title: Grateful Dead Live at The Spectrum on 1979-01-12
lineage: Dolby B Decoded Cassette Master played back on Nakamichi Dragon-Sony PCM R-700 DAT @ 48 kHz (original A-D by J.W. circa 1991); DAT Master played back on a Sony PCM R-500-Digital Audio Labs Carddeluxe-16 bit 48KHz WAV; Editing(Adobe Audition 3.0)-Mastering & Processing(iZotope Ozone 6)-FLAC encoding(dBpoweramp)-tagging(Tag & Re-name)By J.W. :November 2014
description:
Set 1

Jack Straw, Candyman, El Paso, Tennessee Jed, Beat It On Down The Line, Peggy-O, Passenger, Deal

Set 2

Samson & Delilah, It Must Have Been The Roses, Dancin' In The Streets-> Drums-> Not Fade Away-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> Sugar Magnolia, E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text: nice refurbishing of old AUD master The remastered version of the original recording, posted in November, 2014, really brings this show to life. This was my second show. For the nostalgia element, and for the incendiary Dancin-> Garcia jam-> NFA->, five stars. I like the Peggy-O in the 1st set a lot as well. There is a lot of frenzied energy in this recording.

Dancin> Jer and Drummers>Phil>NFA>GDTRFB  The show is somewhat cut from similar early 79 cloth.Keith and Donna were fading away as with Jer's voice. As a Jer lover, The Candyman and Pgggy-o are standouts in the first set. Phil sounds great tonight, kinda the force behind the locomotive that is in need for a push, this decent Jim Wise AUD (much improved than the initial one.) has Phil dropping a bomb or two. Its another of those dates were there few sources and its the only in  AUD. Tonight's major feature lies in the second set, although neither tune is up there as my favs; The Dancin>DrumZ (with Jer and the Drummers having their jam) >(phil)NFA> GDTRFB is the highlight and meat of the second set. Jer is shredding a bit in NFA and the GDTRFB was the only one of the year. Fittingly and rips along! We had a safer ride home than the 5th  i was the driver and kept it steady between the ditches heading to back to Jersey.....1/15 was on deck!!

Super high energy Jerry is on fire for most of this show. I so much want to give it 5 stars, but it's it's hard when Bobby's brutal slide playing messes up what would otherside be a stellar version of GDTRFB. There's also some horrid Bobby slide in NFA, but then Jerry takes off on such a fiery lead that we can forget about the slide solo.

This is the rare show with all uptempo songs in the jam section. No post-drums Jerry ballad. 

The disco dancin' arrangement isn't my favorite in general, but this performance is great. Also, great versions of Samson, Peggy-o, Tennesse Jed, and a blistering Passenger.

Fun anecdote. First, it was snowing on the way to the show, which caused a traffic jam on the NJ Turnpike and caused us to miss most of the first set.

Then, on the way home, there was a radio interview with Billy and Donna. I wish I had a recording. It was a blast. The one part I remember specifically was that the interviewer talked about the new album. He pointed out that, when a band tours with a new album, they usually play songs from the album to promote it. So, why didn't the Dead play any songs from Shakedown St. in this shows? Billy's surprised reply: "We didn't? How about that!"
